Diagnosis.
Recognized by moderate size (2.9–3.5 mm in total length); ovoid, rather tumid, always macropterous body form (
Figs 1, 6
, 
9, 11
); dark brown or castaneous basic coloration; dorsal vestiture with uniformly distributed, brownish, reclining (common) setae, intermixed with moderately or rather sparsely distributed, silvery, sericeous, appressed setae; head across eyes broader than height in frontal view (
Figs 18–21
); antennal segment IV longer than III; long, stout labium slightly exceeding apex of metacoxa; short, scalelike setae (that are uniformly scattered and not partly aggregated) on thoracic pleura and abdominal sterna (
Figs 7, 10, 14–17
, 
48, 51
); thickened or roundly produced margin of ostiole (
Figs 14–17
); fleshy, somewhat lanceolate, apically convergent parempodia (
Figs 25–27
); more or less splayed-out left paramere (
Figs 30, 33
); tumid, elongate-oval right paramere (
Figs 29, 33
); apically folded or keeled phallotheca (
Figs 31, 34
); J-shaped, broad endosoma with well-developed secondary blade (
Figs 32, 35
); thick-rimmed secondary gonopore; rather toughened bursa copulatrix (
Figs 36, 41, 45
); posterior wall with relatively clear interramal sclerite (
Figs 40, 42, 44
); developed medioventral extension of ventral labiate plate (
Figs 39, 43, 46
). See YASUNAGA (2013) for more detailed diagnostic characters.
